<h1>To Lieutenant Colonel Joseph Reed</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Cambridge 30th Novr 1775.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Two days ago I wrote fully to you by Captn Blewerto this Letter I refersince which your favr of the 20th with the agreeable Post[s]cript of the 21st, is come to hand, and demands my acknowledgements for the Civility intended Mrs Washington, by you &amp;ca.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>I have a very singular pleasure in informing of you, that by Express last Night from Cape Ann, I received the glad tidings of the Capture of the Nancy Storeship from London, by Captn Manley, contents as pr the Inclosed Copy (taken by Mr Pierce to save me, you must know, the trouble of innumeration)<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0002-ptr">2</a>He, unluckily, missd the greatest prize in the World; their whole Ordinance; the Ship containing it, being just a head. Buthe could not have got both;<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> and we must be thankful, as I truly am, for this Instance of divine favour; for nothing, surely, ever came more Aproposthat no part of it may slip threw my fingers (for I have no doubt, as this Capture was made in Sight of the other Vessell, of there being some bold push to recover it) I, instantly upon receiving the Acct, orderd four Companies down to protect the StoresTeams to be Impressd to remove them without delay&amp; Colo. Glover to Assemble the Minute men in the Neighbourhood of Cape Ann to secure the removal to places of safety.</p>
<p>The colouring of that affair at Litchmores point has been rather too highThe alacrity of the Riffle-men &amp; Officers upon that occasion did them honour. to which Colo. Pattersons Regiment &amp; some others were equally entitled, except in a few Instances; but the Tide, at that time, was so exceedingly high as to compel a large Circuit before our Men could get to the Causey, by which means the Enemy, except a small Covering Party (distant from the dry land on this side near 400 Yards) had retreated, or were about to Imbarkall the Shot therefore that passd
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-02-02-pb-0464">[464]</span>
were at a great distance; however the Men went to, &amp; over the Causey (except as before mentioned) spiritedly enough.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0004-ptr">4</a></p>
<p>This little Manouvre of the Enemy is nothing more than a prelude. we have certain advice of a Scoundrel from Marblehead, a Man of property, having carried in to General How, a true state of the temper and disposition of the Troops towards the new Inlistment; and hath given him the strongest assurances of the practacability of making himself Master of these Lines in a very short time, from the disaffection of the Soldiery to continue in ServiceI am endeavouring to Counteract himhow effectually, time alone can shew.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0005-ptr">5</a></p>
<p>I began our Bomb Battery on Litchmores point last Night, the workg Party came off at day without having met with any Interruptionthe weather favourd our operation, the Earth being clear of Frost. Not an Officer in the Army but looks for an Attack. this has no effect upon the Connecticut Regiments they are resolved to go off. My best respects to Mrs Reed &amp; any other Friendsbe assurd I am Dr Sir Yr Affecte</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Carter Brown Library, Providence, R.I. ]">RPJCB</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>These letters from Reed to GW have not been found.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Joshua Pierces copy of the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Nancy</span>s inventory has not been identified. An inventory, dated 1 Sept. 1775 and signed by B. Blight, is in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Edward Green wrote to Joshua Green from Cambridge on 3 Dec.: Capt Manly in the Privar, from beaverly came a cross 2 large transports from London, one of which he boardd &amp; took. . . . The other transport was filld with powder, and we fear is gone into Boston, Capt Manly would have taken her also, but 2 Men of Warr appearg in sight, he thought it most prudent to secure what he had got (Clark, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Naval Documents</span>, 2:1247). The report of the second ordnance vessel accompanying the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Nancy</span> on the day of her capture, 28 Nov., is apparently erroneous, however. The brig <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Nancy</span> . . . , Gen. William Howe wrote to the earl of Dartmouth on 27 Nov., is the only ordnance storeship missing that sailed under the convoy of the Phenix man-of-war (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Bell Clark et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Naval Documents of the American Revolution&lt;/i&gt;. 11 vols. to date. Washington, D.C., 1964. ]">Davies, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Documents of the American Revolution</span></span>, 11:19496). Vice Admiral Samuel Graves confirms Howes statement in his narrative for 12 Nov. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Bell Clark et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Naval Documents of the American Revolution&lt;/i&gt;. 11 vols. to date. Washington, D.C., 1964. ]">Clark, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Naval Documents</span></span>, 2:1000).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>For the skirmish at Lechmeres Point on 9 Nov., see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0313" class="document">General Orders, 10 Nov.</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0319" class="document">GW to William Ramsay, 1016 Nov.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0323" class="document">GW to Hancock, 11 Nov. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0419-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>For the report of Benjamin Marstons giving intelligence to General Howe, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0393" class="document">Loammi Baldwin to GW, 26 Nov. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
